# This is a comment. It will not be executed.
print("Hello World.")

Hello World.

There. We just programmed something!¶

What if you wanted to store that text and do something with it later?¶

Easy.¶

In [145]:
greeting = "Hello World."
In [146]:
print(greeting)

Hello World.

This is called "assignment" of a Variable.¶

In [147]:
age = 36

Why's 36 a different color?¶

In [6]:
print(age)

36

Still looks the same...¶

In [7]:
type(age)
Out[7]:
int

Python figured it out for you.¶

You're welcome.¶

But types can be tricky.¶

In [8]:
age + greeting

Assignment can be flexible, too:¶

print(x)

38

Lists¶

Really good at storing something. Anything. And making it accessible.

And they're easy to create:

In [92]:
mylist = [greeting, age, x, y]

That's it. Brackets.¶

And then it's accessible.¶

In [23]:
print(mylist)

['Hello World.', 36, 14, 38]
In [30]:
# Appending is easy.
mylist.append('An appendix')
print(mylist)

['Hello World.', 36, 14, 38, 'An appendix']
In [33]:
# Can we combine them?
secondlist = ['this', 'is', 'just', 'a', 'test', 2]
secondlist + mylist

Operators¶

  • Already touched on them, but these do what you would think:
    • +
    • -
    • *
    • /
  • And there's also modulo %, which gives you the remainder of a division.
  • And ** which raises to a power.
In [37]:
print(3 + 15)
print(3 - 15)
print(3 * 15)
print(15 / 3)
print(15 % 3)
print(15 ** 3)

18
-12
45
5.0
0
3375

Works with Lists, too.¶

But maybe not in the way you thought...¶

In [93]:
intlist = [2,4,9,11,24]
intlist * 2
Out[93]:
[2, 4, 9, 11, 24, 2, 4, 9, 11, 24]

What is truth?¶

Python recognizes the words True and False.

= is for Assigning Variables¶

== is for Truthiness¶

!= is for Falseness¶

In [57]:
# We've always been at war with East Anglia.
1 + 1 == 2
Out[57]:
True
In [54]:
"Stephen" == "Colbert"
Out[54]:
False
In [95]:
stephen = False
colbert = False
print(stephen == colbert)

True
In [56]:
# If / Else Pattern
i = 1
while i < 10:
    if 10 % i == 0:
        print(i)
    else:
        print("Nope")
    i = i + 1

1
2
Nope
Nope
5
Nope
Nope
Nope
Nope

Let's shift gears...¶

Titanic Passenger List¶

  • PassengerId - Unique ID of the passenger
  • Survived - Survived (1) or died (0)
  • Pclass - Passenger's class (1st, 2nd, or 3rd)
  • Name- Passenger's name
  • Sex - Passenger's sex
  • Age - Passenger's age
  • SibSp - Number of siblings/spouses aboard the Titanic
  • Parch - Number of parents/children aboard the Titanic
  • Ticket - Ticket number
  • Fare - Fare paid for ticket
  • Cabin - Cabin number
  • Embarked - Where the passenger got on the ship (C - Cherbourg, S - Southampton, Q = Queenstown)

Let's write a method!¶

  • Repeatable process, kinda like a macro.
  • This one will take in a:
    • DataFrame
    • A list of cut points at which we want to cut the age data.
    • Labels for those cut points.
  • Fill nan or null values with a standard value.
  • Cut the data into age bracket categories.
  • And then return a DataFrame with the added category.
In [189]:
def process_age(df,cut_points,label_names):
    df["Age"] = df["Age"].fillna(-0.5)
    df["Age_categories"] = pd.cut(df["Age"],cut_points,labels=label_names)
    return df
In [185]:
cut_points = [-1,0,5,12,18,35,60,100]
label_names = ["Missing","Infant","Child","Teenager","Young Adult","Adult","Senior"]
tdf = process_age(tdf, cut_points, label_names)
